## Logs
Logs are just powers of a particular number

### Notation
a*a = a<sup>2</sup>

ANYTHING<sup>0</sup> = 1

a<sup>-4</sup> = 1/a<sup>4</sup>

a<sup>n</sup> * a<sup>m</sup> = a<sup>n+m</sup>

a<sup>n</sup> / a<sup>m</sup> = a<sup>n-m</sup>

a<sup>n<sup>m</sup></sup> = a<sup>nm</sup>



### Rule
If a and b are positive this can always be true:

> a<sup>x</sup> = b

> x = log<sub>a</sub>(b)

### Laws of logarithms
log<sub>a</sub>(BC) = log<sub>a</sub>(B) + log<sub>a</sub>(C)

log<sub>a</sub>(B/C) = log<sub>a</sub>(B) - log<sub>a</sub>(C)

log<sub>a</sub>(B<sup>n</sup>) = nlog<sub>a</sub>(B)


### example 2.2.3
find x which satisfies 1.76<sup>x</sup> = 2002

log(1.76<sup>x</sup>) = log(2002)

xlog(1.76) = log(2002)

x = log(2002) / log(1.76)

= 13.45


## Exponential function

Gradient at any point on the graph is equal to the value of y at that point.

### Example 2.3.1
f(t) = 3exp(-5t<sup>2</sup>)

f(0) = 3exp(0) = 3

f(0.4) = 3exp(-5(0.4<sup>2</sup>))

= 1.35...

### Example 2.3.3
Solve the following for x:

e<sup>-2x</sup> = 0.262  
ln(0.262) = -2x  
x = ln(0.262) / -2   
 
### Example 2.3.4
Sketch graph of y = 6e<sup>-2t</sup> , t>0

starts at y=6, decreases rapidly to asymptote at y = 0.


### Example 2.3.5
Sketch graph of y = 7-4e<sup>-2t</sup> , t>0

And express t in terms of y

* when t=0 y is 3
* asymptote at 7
* y increasing

4e<sup>-2t</sup> = 7-y  
e<sup>-2t</sup> = (7-y) / 4  
ln((7-y) / 4) = -2t  
t = ln((7-y) / 4)  /  -2  
